I don't agree with a full-course coverage put in a final project and obliged the student to check each other's work.  The students still have learning curve after the class hence not knowledgeable enough to mimic a BA's work.  I suggest that every week there will be a more simple assignments, e.g. create context diagram this week, DFD next week, etc.   The ones I reviewed where work of Project Managers with too much info in it.
Good introductory course for those moving into the Business Analysis role. But also good if you work on software development projects in other roles like testing or development.

T​his is a great course, and Prof. Ken Reily is fantastic! He is very engaging, funny, keeps your attention focused, and shares plenty of examples throughout the course to help you grasp and immediately visualize the application of concepts. What I loved most is how he shared the textbook on which the course is based, but added his own inputs, experience, knowledge to complement the textbook information, which gave me a lot of confidence to learn from him. The recommended textbook is also superb, I studied the lectures and textbook side-by-side and found it very helpful!
Ken Reily is very detailed and clear in his instruction. The concepts and ideas I learned in Analysis for Business Systems will be useful in my career.
Thanks to University of Minnesota for bringing this course as it has broaden my knowledge.
